There is a need for truly community based participatory research (CBPR)
- Advocating for Creating the research question together
- Projects should be amended to fit community needs and getting feedback from community members
Part of addressing the challenges is by recognizing Indigenous peoples and recognizing the multiple ways of knowing.  We need more time to build trust and relationships

Some of the challenges in doing this work:
- Many conversation programs exclude humans from the equations
- Much of research is siloed, a more holistic approach is needed
- Failure to involve Indigenous people in issues impacting them (eg. animals, waters)

Dr. Anne Ouma shared the results from their work in engaging indigenous people in a talking circle at #ICASSX The works aims to provide a space for dialogue and understanding of traditional environmental governance knowledge in natural resource management https://t.co/XeashV42Fi

They conducted baseline and repeat surveys in remote areas which often had no previous data. The work will help the cities plan for changes in the rapidly changing future. The success of the project is built on partnerships and long term relationships with local communities. https://t.co/PUJbVfELOd
